  "prompt": "Does a phone charger really stop charging when the phone is fully charged?",
  "response": "Yes, most modern phones and chargers are designed to stop charging once the phone reaches 100% battery capacity. This is typically managed by the phone's internal battery management system, which monitors the battery's charge level and regulates the charging process to prevent overcharging.\n\nWhen the battery reaches full capacity, the phone will either stop charging entirely or switch to a trickle charge mode to maintain the battery's full level without overcharging. This helps to preserve battery health and optimize long-term performance.\n\nSome chargers, especially smart chargers, also have built-in mechanisms to reduce or stop power delivery once the device's battery is fully charged. However, while the system is designed to manage this automatically, it is still advisable to disconnect the charger once the phone is fully charged to further ensure battery longevity.",
